<section class="section">
  <div class="container is-max-desktop">
    <div class="columns is-centered has-text-centered">
      <div class="column is-four-fifths">
        <h2 class="title is-3">Abstract</h2>
        <div class="content has-text-justified">
          <p>
            Learning an accurate world model to predict future states is fundamental for Vision-Language-Action (VLA) agents to achieve long-horizon reasoning and effective planning. 
            However, prevailing world models predominantly operate in raw pixel space, which presents two critical challenges:
          </p>
          <p>
            (1) high-dimensional observations introduce significant task-irrelevant perceptual noise, leading to perceptual overfitting, and (2) the prohibitive computational cost of pixel-level autoregressive prediction limits the feasible modeling horizon. 
            In this paper, we propose LatentVLA, a novel paradigm that performs world modeling in a highly compressed latent space. By leveraging a lightweight Adaptive Attention-based Pooling mechanism, we distill high-dimensional visual features into a single, semantically-rich latent world token per frame. This approach significantly reduces computational complexity, enabling the model to scale stably to long-horizon planning steps.
          </p>
          <p>
            Unlike pixel-level models, LatentVLA operates in a high-level semantic space to effectively decouple environmental dynamics from perceptual noise. 
            Across LIBERO, Metaworld, and real-world Piper tasks, LatentVLA with lightweight LoRA fine-tuning on a $\pi_0$ base surpasses the significantly $\pi_{0.5}$ model. This performance gap highlights the efficacy of our semantic abstraction mechanism over traditional scaling.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

